<div id="review_2568644399" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2568644399" />
    <a title="Jess" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/41763158-jess"><img alt="Jess" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1611747988p2/41763158.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2568644399?book_show_action=true">Jan 09, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jess" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jess" href="/user/show/41763158-jess">Jess</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780099388616" href="/book/show/873920.Nights_at_the_Circus">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41763158-jess?shelf=2019">2019</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41763158-jess?shelf=best-heroines">best-heroines</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41763158-jess?shelf=feminism-done-properly">feminism-done-properly</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41763158-jess?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41763158-jess?shelf=best-romances">best-romances</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2568644399" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18117017518471423566">&apos;<i>Wherein does a woman&apos;s honour reside, old chap? In her vagina or in her spirit?</i>&apos;<br/><br/>Sprawling, bawdy, bizarre, repulsive, enchanting. <br/><br/>Angela Carter’s imagination will never cease to astound me. <i>Nights at the Circus</i> is an endlessly original, entirely absorbing magical realism saturated with ambience. Her lush, elegant, <i>ridiculous</i> prose revels in her usual dichotomy of dreamy, psychedelic descriptions brought into sharp focus by the earthy, repellent reminders of filth. How does she do it? <i>How</i>?!<br/><br/>What </span>
  <span id="freeText18117017518471423566" style="display:none">'<i>Wherein does a woman's honour reside, old chap? In her vagina or in her spirit?</i>'<br /><br />Sprawling, bawdy, bizarre, repulsive, enchanting. <br /><br />Angela Carter’s imagination will never cease to astound me. <i>Nights at the Circus</i> is an endlessly original, entirely absorbing magical realism saturated with ambience. Her lush, elegant, <i>ridiculous</i> prose revels in her usual dichotomy of dreamy, psychedelic descriptions brought into sharp focus by the earthy, repellent reminders of filth. How does she do it? <i>How</i>?!<br /><br />What sets this apart from her other works is, for me, the <i>wonderful</i> cast of characters. To name just a few: the Colonel advised by his pet pig (what Sybil says, goes), the mute Abyssinian Princess who tames tigers with waltz, a band of escaped Russian murderesses, and of course, Fevvers. Oh, Fevvers. A fleshly, unapologetic 6"2 winged aerialiste, raised by prostitutes, courted by the Prince of Wales. She makes me want to rejoice in the euphoria of being a woman. Carter’s intellectual and subversive strain of feminism is so utterly inspiring, empowering and <i>fresh</i>. Nowadays, the word ‘feminism’ can be a somewhat uncomfortable one, and one can scarcely help wondering why when we examine the stereotypical ‘strong female character’ trope glorified in the media (seriously, those three words make my stomach turn). Those heartless, cold, ruthless killers who reject all modes of femininity and yet attract all the males in a fifty mile radius. Women who are only on an equal footing to men because they act <i>like</i> men. Should we be praising Angela Carter’s plucky, quirky and body based heroines instead? You decide:<br /><br />‘<i>I raised you up to fly to the heavens, not to brood over a clutch of eggs!</i>’<br /><br />Stuffed full of intelligent allegory and commentary, waspish, honest. Gaudy, graceful, picaresque. Surreal. That is all.<br /><br />Bravissima, Carter!</span>
  <a data-text-id="18117017518471423566" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


