    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1668131754" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1668131754" />
    <a title="Uday" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/34701639-uday"><img alt="Uday" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1668131754?book_show_action=true">Sep 30, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Uday" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Uday" href="/user/show/34701639-uday">Uday</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780099388616" href="/book/show/873920.Nights_at_the_Circus">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1668131754" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3187569890987616776">For me it was, more than anything else, a case of words versus images.<br/><br/>Somewhere in the first twenty pages, our heroine after so enchantingly delighting the audience to her performance, does an act-an act that would&apos;ve been so ghastly indecent to the typical Victorian. . &quot;Better out than in, Sir&quot; - she says to the narrator set out to inscribe her identity, and lets a ripping fart ring around the room. After a taste of her as an image, an icon, &quot;the aerialiste&quot;, the reader should not forget her bo</span>
  <span id="freeText3187569890987616776" style="display:none">For me it was, more than anything else, a case of words versus images.<br /><br />Somewhere in the first twenty pages, our heroine after so enchantingly delighting the audience to her performance, does an act-an act that would've been so ghastly indecent to the typical Victorian. . "Better out than in, Sir" - she says to the narrator set out to inscribe her identity, and lets a ripping fart ring around the room. After a taste of her as an image, an icon, "the aerialiste", the reader should not forget her body, her belches, her farts, food on lips like the fervent drippings of her primal gluttony. Three hundred odd pages of terse but worthwhile prose which follow these words were for me, a struggle for exactly that; how Sophie Fevvers, our "New Woman", wants out of the project of making a Victorian icon out of her modern subjectivity which want the words of the journalist and a narrative, not another Toulouse-Lautrec. Not like the inscrutable visions of middle age sonnets, but present there in her thought and body. Not the image, but the word. Not the cupid, not the "Winged Victory", not even the trapeze artist in tattered fin-de-siecle posters, for a moment, not at least through someone else. The scatological, Menippean answer to your Petrarchan wet-dream. <br /><br />Lizzie and Sophie, the practical and the one who fantasizes, the down to earth, and the one who literally has wings, shuffling within the goblin market of a circus (but her name is Lizzie!), and evading that economy as best they can. There are biting points where Lizzie stops Sophie's Icarus abruptly, forcing a confrontation with the inexorable:<br /><br />"All you can do to earn your living is to make a show of yourself. You're doomed to that. You must give pleasure of the eye, or you're good for nothing. For you, its always a symbolic exchange in the marketplace; you couldn't say you were engaged in productive labor, now, could you, girl?"<br /><br />That's what's been done to Sophie, every time a customer like Rosencruetz comes and enchants on a moonlit night reminiscent of a somnolent Coleridge-ean fantasy, paints symbols through his baritone by saying :<br /><br /> "Azrael, Azrail, Ashriel, Azriel, Azarail, Gabriel; dark angel of many names. Welcome to me, from your home in the third heaven. See, I welcome you with roses no less paradoxically vernal that your presence, who like Perseophone, comes from the Land of the Dead to herald new life!"<br /><br />And every time a Prince of Wales, monuments her in the pretext of celebration in a life-like icicle statue, that struggle begins again, the fight to put wisdom in a cockney accent, to melt that statue with Promethean words, to momentarily set out from the trapeze and perch lightly on a new narrative. As Carter puts it, "our little heroine is a philosopher". (But she is christened "Sophie"!!)<br /><br />p.s.- Watch out for the brilliant sub-plots, Herr M and Mignon, the daguerrotypes, the tigresses, et al. are things of delight, as are the allusions to Poe, Eliot, Yeats, and even damn Shakespeare. </span>
  <a data-text-id="3187569890987616776" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


