<div id="review_2408054572" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2408054572" />
    <a title="Eddie Clarke" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5754022-eddie-clarke"><img alt="Eddie Clarke" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1310052890p2/5754022.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2408054572?book_show_action=true">Dec 28, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Eddie Clarke" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Eddie Clarke" href="/user/show/5754022-eddie-clarke">Eddie Clarke</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5754022-eddie-clarke?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5754022-eddie-clarke?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5754022-eddie-clarke?shelf=abe">abe</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2408054572" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13099959460465512045">Literally, fabulous. I was never less than fully enchanted and engrossed by Carter’s multiplying narratives - but do they add up to a novel? For me the novel has a similar sort of philosophising focus as Candide and Rasselas (and the even same charming magic realism - as if it was a late-20th-century riposte to those Age of Reason texts). I fear a reader wedded to character arcs and sound narrative structure might struggle with this - however, the novel’s symbols and themes are brilliantly coher</span>
  <span id="freeText13099959460465512045" style="display:none">Literally, fabulous. I was never less than fully enchanted and engrossed by Carter’s multiplying narratives - but do they add up to a novel? For me the novel has a similar sort of philosophising focus as Candide and Rasselas (and the even same charming magic realism - as if it was a late-20th-century riposte to those Age of Reason texts). I fear a reader wedded to character arcs and sound narrative structure might struggle with this - however, the novel’s symbols and themes are brilliantly coherent. Carter breathes startling new life into the very well-trodden circus-as-metaphor trope. Heroine aerialiste Fevvers is larger than life, but by the end of the book the journalist and seeker-after-the-truth Walser - a clown who becomes a shaman - steals the show. Magic is real; realism magic.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13099959460465512045" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


